                            <comment id="15150703" author="cott@internetstaff.com" created="Wed, 17 Feb 2016 16:11:47 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m not intimately familiar with SslProtocols. Is it not possible to use:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;SslProtocols.Tls12 | SslProtocols.Tls11 | SslProtocols.Tls&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;... and allow TLS 1.0 - 1.2 without additional configuration?  Making it complicated to be more secure is going to mean people will avoid being more secure. &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/smile.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15150739" author="nsuke" created="Wed, 17 Feb 2016 16:35:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=cott%40internetstaff.com&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;cott@internetstaff.com&quot;&gt;cott@internetstaff.com&lt;/a&gt; yeah, it&apos;s what I want to do after we drop .NET 3.5 API level.&lt;br/&gt;
Doing so now in a straightforward way would break our CI because we don&apos;t have these symbols.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15150865" author="cott@internetstaff.com" created="Wed, 17 Feb 2016 17:49:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Would either None or Default simply allow the client to connect to newer versions of TLS by default?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I realize that means it could connect to a very poorly configured server, but that seems unlikely to be a problem relative to TLS 1.2 since SSLv3 has already been widely disabled.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15151098" author="jensg" created="Wed, 17 Feb 2016 20:18:39 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;because we&apos;re still stuck at .NET 3.5 and equivalent Mono right now.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I still think we should make a break here and have (at least) two libraries. That does not mean that we have to duplicate everything, but two *.csproj with only the relevant files for each version. That way we can improve things where it makes sense and still share 80% of the code.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
